article.headline: LSU goes inside in second half to put game away

article.linkText: No. 3 LSU has no problem passing Texas test
article.story:
BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Louisiana State (No. 3 ESPN/USA Today; No. 2 Associated Press) passed its first big test of
the season with an easy victory Saturday.

<photo1>

	   Aiysha Smith scored 19 points and DeTrina White added 16 as LSU beat No. 15 Texas 76-58. Texas was just the third team
with a winning record LSU has played this season.

	   ''We feel like we can score down low,'' LSU coach Sue Gunter said. ''We
made a conscious effort to look inside in the second half, but we
were also able to rebound and got some transition baskets because
we played better defense.''

	   Heather Schreiber led all scorers with a career-high 20 points
for Texas (6-3).

	   LSU (10-0) shot 48 percent from the field in the first half,
then improved to 54 percent in the second. Texas shot 39 percent in
the first and 33 percent in the second.

	   LSU trailed 37-28 early in the second half, then outscored Texas
34-12 in the final 11 minutes. The Tigers held Texas' leading
scorer, Stacy Stephens, to just six points in the game and no field
goals in the second half.

	   LSU also hit 21 of 28 free throws in the second half. Texas took
just 13 trips to the line in the second, hitting nine free throws.

	   ''We shot the ball much better in the second half, and we got to
the free-throw line, which is what LSU teams are supposed to do,''
Gunter said.

	   Texas scored six consecutive points in the first 90 seconds of
the second half, but LSU had seven consecutive points in a
two-minute stretch to pull to 37-35. LSU had a 13-0 run to go ahead
69-52 with just less than three minutes remaining.

	   Texas never put together a comeback.

	   ''I think when they went on their run, we fell apart,''
Schreiber said. ''We tried to hurry up and score on the offensive
end rather than looking for the best shot.''

	   Texas coach Jody Conradt said her team was ''manhandled'' in the
second half.

	   ''We lost our will to fight back,'' Conradt said. ''We lost
patience on both ends of the floor, and everyone went off on their
own agenda to try and save the day.''

	   White had 12 rebounds, and Smith had seven boards for LSU.
Doneeka Hodges scored 13 points and Temeka Johnson scored 10.

	   Stephens had 12 rebounds and Kala Bowers scored 11 points for
the Longhorns, who are 0-3 on the road.

	   ''This was a really good win for us,'' Gunter said.
